The lion is a well-muscled cat with a long body, large head, and short legs. Size and appearance vary considerably between the sexes. The male‚Äôs outstanding characteristic is his mane, which varies between different individuals and populations. It may be entirely lacking; it may fringe the face; or it may be full and shaggy, covering the back of the head, neck, and shoulders and continuing onto the throat and chest to join a fringe along the belly. In some lions the mane and fringe are very dark, almost black, giving the cat a majestic appearance. Manes make males look larger and may serve to intimidate rivals or impress prospective mates. A full-grown male is about 1.8‚Äì2.1 metres (6‚Äì7 feet) long, excluding the 1-metre tail; he stands about 1.2 metres high at the shoulder and weighs 170‚Äì230 kg (370‚Äì500 pounds). The female, or lioness, is smaller, with a body length of 1.5 metres, a shoulder height of 0.9‚Äì1.1 metres, and a weight of 120‚Äì180 kg. The lion‚Äôs coat is short and varies in colour from buff yellow, orange-brown, or silvery gray to dark brown, with a tuft on the tail tip that is usually darker than the rest of the coat.
